Say you've got the following setup: a `ui::Widget` is added to a `ui::ListView`, then sometime later, instead of using `removeChild` on the `ui::ListView`, you  call [`my_widget->removeFromParent()`](https://github.com/cocos2d/cocos2d-x/blob/v3/cocos/2d/CCNode.cpp#L994), the `ListView::innerContainer::removeChild` gets called, instead of [`ListView::removeChild`](https://github.com/cocos2d/cocos2d-x/blob/v3/cocos/ui/UIListView.cpp#L298), leaving `ListView::_items` untouched. So if you kept calling [`my_listview->addChild(my_widget)`](https://github.com/cocos2d/cocos2d-x/blob/v3/cocos/ui/UIListView.cpp#L271), you'd get an infinite amount of `my_widget` pointers in the `_items` vector, because the linked code would never get called.

Some non-compiling example code:

```
ui::Button* my_button = ui::Button::create(whatever);
ui::ListView* my_listview = ui::ListView::create(whatever);

my_listview->addChild(my_button);
//through ListView::addChild, my_listview->_items->push_back is called, and my_listview->innerContainer gets my_button added
my_button->removeFromParent();
//effectively innerContainer->removeChild(my_button) is called
// now my_listview->_items still has my_button in it, size=1, while innerContainer does not
my_listview->addChild(my_button);
// now my_listview->_items still has my_button in it and a copy of the pointer, size=2
```

Hope this is clear enough. Not sure what a solution would be, beyond checking to make sure the type of `_parent` doesn't have `_items` or something, but that's pretty clunky.
